          </TabsList>

          <TabsPanel id="faq-panel-1" labelledby="faq-tab-1" selected>
            <Accordion>
              <AccordionItem title="Why is this hackathon being organized?">
                <p>
                  The CIVICUS Digital Democracy Initiative (DDI) supports local digital innovations that expand civic space. However, many civil society organizations (CSOs) in Eastern Europe and Central Asia face challenges in developing and deploying such tools. This hackathon, implemented by the Metamorphosis Foundation and Civic Literacy Initiative, aims to:<br><br>
                  <ul>
                    <li>Address real-world challenges CSOs face in areas like fact-checking, digital security, and youth campaigning.</li>
                    <li>Build the capacity of local actors to create and pilot their own solutions.</li>
                    <li>Provide funding and mentorship to turn promising ideas into sustainable projects.</li>
                    <li>Foster a regional network of civic tech innovators.</li>
                  </ul>
                </p>
              </AccordionItem>
              <AccordionItem title="Who are the organizers?">
                <ul>
                  <li>The <strong>Metamorphosis Foundation</strong> is the lead partner, responsible for overall project coordination and financial administration.</li>
                  <li>The <strong>Civic Literacy Initiative (CLi)</strong> is the lead contractor, responsible for designing the hackathon content and providing mentorship to the teams.</li>
                  <li>The program is funded by the <strong>CIVICUS Digital Democracy Initiative (DDI)</strong>.</li>
                </ul>
              </AccordionItem>
            </Accordion>
          </TabsPanel>
          <TabsPanel id="faq-panel-2" labelledby="faq-tab-2">
            <Accordion>
              <AccordionItem title="What do the selected teams receive?">
                <p>
                  The five selected teams will receive a comprehensive support package to bring their ideas to life. This includes:<br><br>
                  <ul>
                    <li>A <strong>$8,000 sub-grant</strong> to fund the development and piloting of their solution.</li>
                    <li>An <strong=all-expenses-paid trip</strong> for team members to participate in the in-person hackathon in Bangkok, Thailand (1-5 November 2025).</li>
                    <li><strong>Expert mentorship</strong> before, during, and after the hackathon to provide technical, design, and strategic guidance.</li>
                    <li>An opportunity to join a <strong>vibrant regional network</strong> of changemakers working on similar issues.</li>
                  </ul> 
                </p>
              </AccordionItem>
              <AccordionItem title="What are the hackathon's thematic areas?">
                <p>
                  Applicants must propose a solution that addresses one of the following four thematic areas. 
                  <br><br>
                  <ul>
                    <li>Community Fact-Checking</li>
                    <li>Secure Organizing Methods</li>
                    <li>Digital Security</li>
                    <li>Youth-Led Campaigning</li>
                  </ul>
                  <br>
                  You can find detailed descriptions and problem statements for each on the <a href="/scenarios" target="_blank"><strong>Scenarios</strong></a> page of our website.
                </p>
              </AccordionItem>
              <AccordionItem title="What is the expected outcome of the projects?">
                <p>
                  The goal of the in-person hackathon is for each team to develop a <strong>working prototype</strong> of their solution. This could be a clickable wireframe, a piece of code, a detailed process map, or another tangible model. The  five participating teams will be expected to develop this prototype further after the hackathon, transforming it from a prototype to a <strong>pilot initiative</strong> that is tested with a real user community.
                </p>
              </AccordionItem>
            </Accordion>
          </TabsPanel>
          <TabsPanel id="faq-panel-3" labelledby="faq-tab-3">
            <Accordion>
              <AccordionItem title="Who is eligible to apply?">
                <p>
                  This call is for civil society organizations and activist teams based in one of the seven target countries: <strong>Albania, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Kosovo, Moldova, Montenegro, North Macedonia, and Turkey</strong>. We welcome teams with diverse skills, including developers, designers, researchers, project managers, and advocates who are passionate about using technology to strengthen democracy.
                </p>
              </AccordionItem>
              <AccordionItem title="Can I apply as a group or only as an individual?">
                <p>
                  Only applications from registered civic organisations or informal groups will be considered. This means that a successful proposal will include at least 3 team members committed to work on it.
                </p>
              </AccordionItem>
              <AccordionItem title="How can I apply?">
                <p>
                  Applicants should apply online via an online form available on the open call page. Applicants will be asked to fill the scenario pitch with their initial solution proposal but also a series of questions about their eligibility. Only complete applications submitted before the deadline will be considered for review.<br><br>Before applying, we recommend that you read this applicants' guide website and review the <a href="/files/DigitalDemocracyHackathon-OpenCall.pdf" target="_blank">Application Form</a> 
                </p>
              </AccordionItem>
            </Accordion>
          </TabsPanel>
          <TabsPanel id="faq-panel-4" labelledby="faq-tab-4">
            <Accordion>
              <AccordionItem title="How many teams will be selected?">
                <p>
                  One candidate proposal will be selected for each scenario, for a total of 5 teams.<br><br>All of the selected teams will be expected to join the event in Bangkok.
                </p>
              </AccordionItem>
              <AccordionItem title="How will the applications be reviewed? ">
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    <strong>Relevance to thematic areas:</strong> 1-20 from unrelated to highly aligned
                  </li> 
                  <li>
                    <strong> Clarity and feasibility of the idea:</strong> 1-20 from vague or unrealistic to highly feasible and actionable

                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>Civic impact and innovation potential:</strong> 1–25 from low-impact/standard to innovative and high-impact
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>Team capacity and motivation:</strong> 1–15 from unclear or weak capacity to strong and committed team
                  <li>
                    <strong>Inclusiveness and values alignment:</strong> 1–10 from not demonstrated to clearly embedded
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>Geographic and Demographic Balance:</strong> 1–10 from overrepresented or imbalanced to strongly contributing to diversity
                  </li>
                </ul>
                <br>
                <p>
                  See the <a href="#selection-criteria"><strong>Selection criteria</strong></a> for more information.
                </p>
              </AccordionItem>
              <AccordionItem title="Can I submit more than one application?">
                <p>
                  Yes, you can submit one proposal for each scenario.
                </p>
              </AccordionItem>
              <AccordionItem title="Can I submit my application in a language other than English?">
                <p>
                  All information provided in the application form must be in English. However, we encourage developing the prototypes in your native languages. 
                </p>
              </AccordionItem>
              <AccordionItem title="Can I use AI to translate my documents to English?">
                <p>
                  Manual or automated translations are acceptable, as long as the resulting content is legible. Be mindful that AI translations can sometimes change the meaning of your text, or hallucinate words if it does not understand some of the technical/context-specific words or acronyms that you have submitted for translation. Reviewers will not try to guess the meaning of your proposal if some of its parts do not make sense.
                </p>
              </AccordionItem>
              <AccordionItem title="Can I change my application once it is submitted?">
                <p>
                  Once submitted, you cannot change your application because we start immediately with the review.
                </p>
              </AccordionItem>
              <AccordionItem title="When is the submission deadline?">
                <p>
                  The open call will be open until <strong>22 September 2025</strong>.<br><br>
                  The complete timeline is <a href="#timeline">here</a>.
                </p>
              </AccordionItem>
            </Accordion>
          </TabsPanel>
